# anpia_daily.cron.example -- REQ-ANPIA-REQ-01-D02
#
# FALLBACK ONLY. Prefer the systemd service + timer
# (05_IMPLEMENTATION/deployment/systemd/anpia-daily.{service,timer}) --
# it gives Persistent=true (catch-up after downtime), proper logging to
# journald, and hardened service isolation that plain cron does not.
#
# This file is an EXAMPLE for reference only. It is NOT installed by any
# script in this repository, and nothing in this task has added it (or
# anything else) to any crontab on any machine.
#
# CRON_TZ requires a reasonably modern cron implementation (e.g. cronie,
# Vixie cron with CRON_TZ support). If the target's cron does NOT honor
# CRON_TZ, do not assume the schedule below is correct -- convert
# 12:00 Asia/Colombo (UTC+05:30, no DST) to the system's actual crontab
# timezone by hand instead of relying on this line, and document that
# conversion at install time.

CRON_TZ=Asia/Colombo

# minute hour day month weekday command
0 12 * * * ANPIA_PROJECT_ROOT=/opt/anpia ANPIA_PYTHON_BIN=/opt/anpia/.venv/bin/python3 ANPIA_ENV_FILE=/etc/anpia/.env /opt/anpia/05_IMPLEMENTATION/deployment/run_anpia_daily.sh >> /opt/anpia/09_OUTPUTS/logs/anpia_daily_cron.log 2>&1

# Notes for whoever installs this manually (`crontab -e` as the anpia-svc
# user -- never root):
#   - cron does not provide systemd's Persistent=true catch-up behavior --
#     a missed run (VM down at 12:00) is simply skipped, not caught up.
#   - cron does not prevent overlapping runs on its own -- this is safe
#     here ONLY because anpia_daily_pipeline.py's own file lock
#     (09_OUTPUTS/logs/anpia_daily_pipeline.lock) rejects a second
#     concurrent run with exit code 7; do not remove that lock.
#   - Redirect stdout/stderr to a real log file (shown above) since cron
#     jobs have no journald integration by default.
